2018 Edition

Challenge: What is the future selling price of a home?¶

A home is often the largest and most expensive purchase a person makes in his or her lifetime. Ensuring homeowners have a trusted way to monitor this asset is incredibly important.

In this competition, students are required to develop a full-fledged approach to make predictions about the future sale prices of homes. A full-fledged approach constist, at least, in the following steps:

  • Descriptive statistics about the data
  • Data cleaning and pre-processing
  • Defining a modeling approach to the problem
  • Build such a statistical model
  • Validate the outcome of the model

Now, should you ask a home buyer to describe their dream house, they probably wouldn't begin with describing features such as the height of the basement ceiling or the proximity to a railroad. As you will see, the dataset we use in this competition proves that many more features influence price negotiations than the number of bedrooms or a white-picket fence.

With 79 explanatory variables describing (almost) every aspect of residential homes in a small city in the US, this competition challenges you to predict the final price of each home.

The dataset¶

File descriptions¶

  • train.csv - the training dataset
  • test.csv - the test dataset
  • data_description.txt - full description of each column

Goal of the challenge¶

It is your job to predict the sales price for each house. For each Id in the test set, you must predict the value of the SalePrice variable.

Metric¶

Notebooks are evaluated on Root-Mean-Squared-Error (RMSE) between the logarithm of the predicted value and the logarithm of the observed sales price. (Taking logs means that errors in predicting expensive houses and cheap houses will affect the result equally.)

In [1]:
import numpy as np

def rmse(pred,obs):
    predLog=[np.log(p) for p in pred]
    obsLog=[np.log(o) for o in obs]
    err=0
    for (o,p) in zip(obsLog,predLog):
        err+=(o-p)**2
    return np.sqrt(err/len(pred))

#test
rmse([1,2],[2,4])
Out[1]:
0.6931471805599453

1. Descriptive statistics about the data¶

1.1 Categories¶

Firstly, let's look at the available CSV data.

The data categories don't really match what an average buyer would look for in a house. Firstly because there are 79 categories - no buyer will look for as much informations, and some categories are quite unexpected, like the roof type. We expect that some factors will contribute a lot more to the price of the house than other ones.

Some data types are quantitative (integers for example) and others are categorical (strings), and both of them seem to matter. Our model will thus need to take into account both of them, which is not that straight-forwward.

We notice that some categories are almost empty, like Alley, so we will have to clean the data set.

Some categories take the same value for each house, like the Street, sothey don't seems very useful.

We have already noticed that some categories have linked values, such as BsmtFinSF2 and BsmtUnfSF. It will thus be necessary for our model to take into account the correlation between some inputs.

We take into consideration that two categories are id and salePrice and are not to be considered as input parameters.

1.2 Import and basic cleaning¶

Now, we want to do some statistic observations. To do so, let's define a few functions to fetch the data and its relevant attibutes.

We'll create the following objects:

name type description
data list(dict(string)) example: data[n]["alley"] represents the alley parameter of the n-th house
data_quant list(dict(string)) same as data, but only for the quantitative data
data_qual list(dict(float)) same as data, but only for the categorical data
data_forceQual list(dict(float)) same as data, but all the data has been force-cast to floats, more below
data_fq list(list(float)) same as above but with a list instead of a dictionnary
params list(string) all the 79 parameters
params_qual list(string) only the categorical parameters, as defined by the function isQual(param)
params_quant list(string) only the quantitative parameters, as defined by the function isQual(param)
prices list(float) an array with all the 1200 prices
In [2]:
def import_data(path):
    """
    returns 'data' (see 1.2 statistics), the parameteters detected, and the prices
    """
    f=open(path)
    lines=f.readlines()
    f.close()
    for i in range(len(lines)):
        lines[i]=lines[i].split(",")
        lines[i][-1]=lines[i][-1][0:-1]
    
    #parameters: [MSSubClass, MSZoning, ..., Sale Condition]
    params=lines[0][1:-1]
    
    #only the house data
    lines=lines[1:]
    
    #price
    prices=[l[-1] for l in lines]
    
    #data
    data=[{} for i in range(len(lines))]
    for dataNumber in range(len(lines)):
        for paramNumber in range(len(params)):
            data[dataNumber][params[paramNumber]]=lines[dataNumber][paramNumber+1]
    return (data,params,prices)

def isQual(data,param):
    """
    returns True if the specified parameter of the data represents a number
    """
    for d in data:
        try:
            float(d[param])
        except ValueError:
            return False
    return True

def selectQual(data,params):
    """
    returns 'data_qual' (see 1.2 statistics) and the categorical parameters
    """
    ret=[]
    qualParams=[]
    for p in params:
        if isQual(data,p):
            qualParams.append(p)
    for d in data:
        ret.append({})
        for qp in qualParams:
            ret[-1][qp]=d[qp]
    return ret,qualParams

def selectQuant(data,params):
    """
    returns 'data_quant' (see 1.2 statistics) and the quantitative parameters
    """
    ret=[]
    quantParams=[]
    for p in params:
        if not isQual(data,p):
            quantParams.append(p)
    for d in data:
        ret.append({})
        for qp in quantParams:
            ret[-1][qp]=d[qp]
    return ret,quantParams

Everything seems to work well... but wait, why is house #1's LotFrontage a quantitative data?

Diving into train.csv, we observe that several entries have their LotFrontage parameter set to NA, which makes out algorithm view the LotFrontage parameter as being quantitative. We thus need the data_forceQual, where every datum is cast to a numeric value (label encoding).

Further observation, numbers in the original CSV file are only non-negative integers. We'll thus convert strings into negative integers in order to differentiate them.

In [4]:
import copy
def forceQual(data,params):
    paramsValue={}
    ret=copy.deepcopy(data) # <--- beware of mutable/immutable! ret=data modifies the data!
    for p in params:
        paramsValue[p]=[]
    for i in range(len(ret)):
        for j in range(len(params)):
            p=params[j]
            d=ret[i][p]
            try:
                #datum is cast to a float
                ret[i][p]=float(d)
            except ValueError:
                #datum can't be cast to a float
                try:
                    #identical datum has already been force cast to a negative int
                    val=paramsValue[p].index(d)
                    ret[i][p]=-val-1
                except ValueError:
                    #identical datum has never been force cast to a negative int
                    paramsValue[p].append(d)
                    val=paramsValue[p].index(d)
                    ret[i][p]=-val-1
    return ret

This scatter plot matrix (aka pair plot) gives an in-depth detail of the mutual behavior of the most correlated variables. We can observe a few trends:

  • GarageArea - GarageCars: the bigger the garage, the more we can fit cars inside
  • GarageArea - OverallQuall: the bigger the garage, the better the overall quality
  • GarageArea - YearBuilt: if the house is recent, the lower bound for the uncertainty on the size of the garage is high
  • OverallQual - YearBuilt: it is clear that recent houses are of a better quality and vice versa, but the confidence interval of one parameter given the other is high.

And that's it for the mutual behavior analysis of functions. In a nutshell:

Mutual behavior: most parameters are not correlated. The ones who do are positively correlated. The most correlated parameters are the ones we expected, ie they are the one who reflects obvious behavior, eg bigger garage=more cars can be fit into the garage.

3. Neural network¶

The main observation about the data is its mixed composition - there are both categorical and quantitative data and both are equally important. Untill now, we've used a label encoding for the categorical data but it won't be relevant to plug label-encoded categorical data into a NN. Therefore we'll opt for one-hot encoding.

We'll be left with a lot of variables, which affects the NN's performance. Considerations about entropy shows that some parameters carry almost no information. Therefore, we'll compress data into a reduced set of parameters using PCA.

The compressed data will then be pluggen into a NN whose parameters will be chosen thanks to a bayesian optimization.

3.1 Pre-processing¶

3.1.1 Categorical variables processing¶

Untill now, no particular attention has been focused on the processing of categorical variables - they were just cast to negative integers. Let's do something more relevant to convert every categorical variable into categorical ones.

Categorical parameters can either have an order (eg: bad-good-excellent) or not. Those who have an order are cast to positive integers according to their order. We apply a 1-hot encoding to the other non-orderable parameters.

This also means that orderable parameters are treated 'manually'. We base our order on this document. This gets reflected onto the orderable python variable, which states, for example, that a LandSlope parameter of value Sev will be cast to a 2.

for i in range(len(data_q)):
    for p in data_q[i]:
        if p in orderable:
            # orderable value
            data_q[i][p]=orderable[p].index(data_q[i][p])
        else:
            if data_q[i][p]=="NA":
                data_q[i][p]=0
            try:
                # categorical value
                data_q[i][p]=float(data_q[i][p])
            except ValueError:
                # non-orderable value
                if p not in non_orderable:
                    non_orderable[p]=[]
                if data_q[i][p] not in non_orderable[p]:
                    non_orderable[p].append(data_q[i][p])

                    
import pandas as pd
df=pd.DataFrame(data_q)
dummies=pd.get_dummies(df,prefix=non_orderable.keys())

params=dummies.columns.values
params_vals=np.transpose(dummies.values)

print("Number of parameters:",len(params))
print("A few values:")
for i in [0,3,55,56,57]:
    print("parameter #{}: {}, first values: {}".format(i, params[i], params_vals[i][0:10]))

3.1.2 Entropy observations¶

Now let's take a look at the amount of information carried out by the parameters by mapping the entropy in ascending order:

In [18]:
import scipy as sp

proba=[]
for p in params_vals :
    distr={}
    for d in p:
        if d in distr:
            distr[d]+=1/1200
        else:
            distr[d]=1/1200
    proba.append([distr[k] for k in distr])

entropy=[sp.stats.entropy(p) for p in proba]

plt.plot(sorted(entropy))
Out[18]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7f8808489c50>]

We can observe that some parameters carry way more information than other and that most don't carry a lot of information, which leaves the door open to parameter reduction.

We might be tempted to ditch out the parameters that carry an entropy lower than a certain treshold, but that's not the most relevant technique. Rather, we'll compress the amount of parameters using a PCA analysis.

3.1.3 PCA¶

Principal component analysis (PCA) converts the set of correlated variables into a set of values of uncorrelated varaiables (called principal components). This procedures allows to reduce the number of variables, which is important for the deep learning, and to make the information less redundant.

In [16]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.metrics import explained_variance_score
from numpy.linalg import eigh

explainedVariance=0
tresholdPassed=0
explainedVarianceList=[]
for k in range(len(params_vals)):
    pca=PCA(n_components=k)
    pca.fit(params_vals)
    
    cov=np.cov(params_vals)
    eigenval,eigenvec=eigh(cov)
    u=eigenvec[:k]
    z=np.dot(u,params_vals)
    xappr=np.dot(np.transpose(u),z)

    explainedVariance=explained_variance_score(params_vals,xappr)
    explainedVarianceList+=[explainedVariance]
    if explainedVariance>0.95:
        if tresholdPassed==0:
            tresholdPassed=k

print(tresholdPassed,"variables are enough to explain",explainedVarianceList[tresholdPassed],"of the variance. We'll thus keep this number of parameters.")
plt.plot(explainedVarianceList)

72 variables are enough to explain 0.9869854894228464 of the variance. We'll thus keep this number of parameters.
Out[16]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7f53c85761d0>]
In [19]:
pca=PCA(n_components=tresholdPassed)
pca.fit(params_vals)
cov=np.cov(params_vals)

components=pca.components_
x_train=np.transpose(components)[0:1000]
x_test=np.transpose(components)[1000:1200]

We did't expected such a curve for the explained variance. Usually, A few parameters explain most of what is happening and a lot of parameters don't add that much informations, leading to a curve that looks more like a square root. However, there is a brutal step around a 60-parameters PCA compression. This might be due to the binary variables from the one-hot encoding that behave differently from the other ones.

In any case, we retain 168 parameters and all the compressed data is in the python variable components.

Now let's take a wild guess: more layers and more units mean more intelligence in the network, right? By growing the network bigger, it is likely that the predictions it makes are going to get better - but the computation time is likely to get bigger too.

First observation, the rectified linear function ('relu', x from 27 to 35) is the most relevant activation function.

However, when observing the MSE of MLPs that used this function, some results seems counterintuitive: the "the bigger the better" assumption concerning the number of layers and units of the MLP is not always verified; results might differ but as we write this a 1x40 MLP performs better than a 4x40 MLP. Therefore we need a more clever way to find the optimal layer configurations of our MLP.

There's also the grid search parameter that we can play with. Let's do a grid search on it on a 3x20 relu MLP.

3.3 Bayesian optimisation on the neural network¶

We already found the best activation function, now let's use a bayesian optimisation to find the best neural network shape. To begin with, let's find a 4-layer MLP with an optimized number of hidden inputs.

In [46]:
from sklearn.gaussian_process import GaussianProcessRegressor
from sklearn.gaussian_process.kernels import RBF
max_nb_units=200

def rmseNN(nb_units):
    mlp=MLPRegressor(hidden_layer_sizes=[nb_units for i in range(4)],max_iter=1000,solver="lbfgs")
    mlp.fit(x_train,y_train)
    return rmse(y_test,mlp.predict(x_test))

hList=[[10],[50]]
rmseList=[rmseNN(h[0]) for h in hList]
print(rmseList)

while len(hList)<3:
    
    rmseMin=np.min(rmseList)
    gpr=GaussianProcessRegressor(
        kernel=1*RBF(length_scale=5),
        alpha=1e-3
    )
    gpr.fit(hList,rmseList)
    gprPred,gprStd=gpr.predict([[x] for x in range(1,max_nb_units)],return_std=True)
    gprLow=[p-2*s for (p,s) in zip(gprPred,gprStd)]
    gprHigh=[p+2*s for (p,s) in zip(gprPred,gprStd)]
    expectedImprovement=[(0 if (rmseMin-g<0) else rmseMin-g) for g in gprLow]
    hList.append([np.argmax(expectedImprovement)+1])
    rmseList.append(rmseNN(hList[-1][0]))
    
    print(hList[-1][0],rmseList[-1])
    
    plt.plot(range(1,max_nb_units),gprPred,'b')
    plt.plot(range(1,max_nb_units),gprLow,'g')
    plt.plot(range(1,max_nb_units),gprHigh,'r')

[0.11399583632290106, 0.11725526117735244]
93 0.12650249001663166

This is the output of a gaussian process on two values. In blue, the expected RMSE, in green and red, the boundaries of a 95% confidence interval on this prediction.

The expected improvement is the difference between the lowest observed value (0.1139) and the green curve - the highest point on it has in the x-axis the number of hidden units to try next. For computation time purpose we can't go further for now.

Conclusion¶

Pre-processing and cleaning the data¶

Understanding of the data¶

Of the 79 variables provided, 33 were categorical and 44 were continuous. As our response variable, Sale Price, is continuous, we used regression models.

How did we handle categorical variables?¶

Our first objective was to combine these data sets into a single set both to account for the total missing values. We had to fully understand all the classes for each categorical variable to give them a quantitative value (ordinal or nominal).

Ordinal categories¶

For the ordinal variables, we assigned a number to their relative rank. For example, Exellent becomes 5, Goood 4, Typical 3, Fair 2, Poor 1.

Nominal categories¶

We proceeded those categories doing the 1-hot encoding.

Missing data¶

To handle the missing values, we noticed a class of NA in some categorical parameters. So we converted all the NA categorical values in 0 (zero), a quantitative value.

PCA to remove the parameters with low variance¶

We noticed that some parameters were much more important than othes. We also understood that some parameters were strongly correlated. We wanted to remove the categories with very low variance (since they offer little predictive power to models). So we applied the Principal component analysis (PCA), to find an optimal number of parameters to reduce the cost of the next calculations. Since we applied the PCA, at the end we will not be able to find easily the most important features.

Models¶

model pros cons RMSE
linear model very simple to implement and interpret low performance 0.214
neural network gives the best results very complex to find the right parameters best ones around 0.110
ridge regression no variable selection, no distribution requirement, does not suffers from multicolinearity not the best results of all models 0.221
lasso regression no distribution requirements suffers from multicolinearity, variable selection 0.183
gradient boosting good performances easily overfit, long, many hyperparameters that are hard to tweak 0.166 for SkLearn, 0.154 for LightGBM
multivariate k-nearest neighbors quick, simple to implement, no distribution requirements bad initialization can cause bad results 0.249
decision trees handles outsiders well, easy to interpret, good for few categories variables easily overfit 0.296
random forest same as decision trees, plus fast and scalable easily overfit 0.194

We could have used cross-validation to estimatethe accuracy of the performance of our predictive models.
